tonio, Carmela, Ettore, Pasquale, Serafino, Vito.","Italian: probably a nickname from Calabrese dialect <i>vesciu</i> ‘cross-eyed person’ or <i>vescia</i> ‘kind of mushroom’. In Italy the surname is most frequent in Calabria, specifically in Lamezia Terme in Catanzaro province."]}]},{"name":"Madeleine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."],"variants":[{"name":"Madaline","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madeline","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madalene","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madelene","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madelaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Madeleine ."]},{"name":"Madoline","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Madeleine ."]},{"name":"Madlyn","meanings":["Modern variant of   Madeleine  , influenced by the productive suffix <i>-lyn</i>;  see  Lynn ."]},{"name":"Madelyn","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Madeleine de Vesci was born in 1007, in Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France. She married Eustace de Burgo in 1021. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 12 May 1060, in her hometown, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1007–12 May 1060":"1007–12. mai 1060","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1007–1060":"1007–1060","1007":"1007","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1005":"1005","12 May 1060":"12. mai 1060","1057":"1057","3 July 1057":"3. juuli 1057","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Burcy, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1007–12 May 1060":"1007–12. toukokuuta 1060","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1007–1060":"1007–1060","1007":"1007","about 1030":"noin 1030","1005":"1005","12 May 1060":"12. toukokuuta 1060","1057":"1057","3 July 1057":"3. heinäkuuta 1057","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Burcy, Calvados, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1007–12 May 1060":"1007–12 mai 1060","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1007–1060":"1007–1060","1007":"1007","about 1030":"environ 1030","1005":"1005","12 May 1060":"12 mai 1060","1057":"1057","3 July 1057":"3 juillet 1057","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Burcy, Calvados, Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"Madeleine de Vesci e